The evidence we present here for strong and rising trust in the New Zealand Police comes from a national panel sample that repeatedly measures the same individuals in successive years. The NZAVS sample is randomly selected from New Zealand electoral role – a privilege unique to New Zealand’s research community. NZAVS time series data possess an integrity that brings confidence to these preliminary findings. However, the causal processes underpinnings of strong and increasing trust in the New Zealand Police remain unclear. Clarifying why the New Zealand Police is so highly trusted holds importance for New Zealanders who which to sustain such confidence, and may be important for countries who experience lower confidence in their police forces and seek to improve trust. Although New Zealanders express a strong willingness to engage with the police, the causes for the a slight decline in such willingness merit future investigation.
